column168: XPO Logistics terminal XSA experienced a UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 release from a 5-gallon poly pail and a Non-Regulated Xcelente release from a 2-liter poly jug. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed all 5-gallons of the UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 released as all as all 2-liters of the Xcelente released together. The products impacted a 12’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor and a 12’ x 4’ area of the concrete lot below due to forklift punctures. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged empty jugs and spend absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On September 1, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1789 was crushed during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site. EWI personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and swept them in with hand tools. All freight was wiped down and repalletized for further handling by R+L terminal personnel. All spent absorbents, cleanup debris, and the empty, damaged 5-gallon pail were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drum that was labeled and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: On September 1, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon bucket of acetone was damaged during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES&H to remediate the impacted site.  Crews observed that the released material evaporated prior to their arrival and there was no recoverable material remaining in the trailer. One (1) 5-gallon bucket of product was punctured and released all its contents. No other buckets were damaged and the crew determined it was safe for the driver to continue to his destination. The terminal manager indicated they would offload the freight there and repackage as needed.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: On September 6, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote containing UN1805 was damaged due to falling off the lift gate and released approximately eighty (80) gallons of product to the soil. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site. SET personnel deployed poly sheeting around the impacted areas and patched the one (1) damaged tote. The crew returned the next day to perform a tote transfer. SET personnel conducted a gravity transfer of the remaining material from the damaged tote into one (1) new 330-gallon tote provided by on-site management. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. Once neutralized, SET personnel utilized a back hoe to remove the impacted soil. The excavated area was backfilled with clean soil, graded to match pre-existing topography, and covered with erosion matting to promote vegetative growth. All impacted soil was collected and containerized into one (1) roll off and staged on-site pending waste profiling for disposal purposes. One (1) background and one (1) confirmation sample were obtained from the site, placed into laboratory approved containers, and transported under chain of custody protocol to the laboratory.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN3272 Disperbyk-161 release from a 55-gallon steel drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 53-gallons of material released to a 58’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot below the dock and a 15’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. The impacted trailer, concrete lot, and trench drain that flows to the onsite OWS were all pressure washed. All impacted water and skimmed material from the trench drain were collected and containerized into an additional 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized with absorbent pads into a 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: When picking up freight to load into trailer, forklift operator placed the forkblades of his forklift into the pallet of freight and when doing so the forkblades struck the bottom of a drum that was staged on the pallet that had fallen in between a broken board on the pallet. When the drum was struck by the forkblade it punctured the drum which in turn contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column169: If a piece of dunnage like a sheet of cardboard was placed on the pallet before the freight was staged on it or better quality pallets were used maybe this unintentional release could have been prevented.

column168: While loading freight into a trailer, forklift operator drove the forkblades of his forklift into the bottom of two drums that were already staged in the trailer consequently puncturing them and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into recovery containers as were the two punctured drums.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to help these types of unintentional releases from occurring. A meeting was held with the dockworkers about this event and what they can do to help prevent these types of unintentional releases going forward.

column168: On September 12, 2023, at 1550 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Dickson, Tennessee regarding the release of approximately (40) gallons of Isopropyl Alcohol 70% (UN1219, 3, II). The shipment had 26 pallets of an unknown amount of boxes. Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed that the release was from 26 crushed cardboard boxes all together containing (312) 16-ounce bottles. The release was due to too much weight on top of the boxes, crushing the boxes and bottles inside, and contained to a 5’x 4’ area of the trailer floor. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (4) 55-gallon DF which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column168: On September 8, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of paint (UN1263) were damaged by a skid and released approximately six (6) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel deployed granular absorbents, absorbent pads and cleaners to the paint primer-impacted trailer interior and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents, impacted pallets and absorbent pads were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for terminal disposal. Damaged pails were patched up and over-packed into one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LSH experienced a customer location release of UN1791 Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5% from a 55-gallon poly drum. column168: During the QC process in the warehouse at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility, the drum was removed from the pallet to be weighed. The drum was weighed and set aside for approximately 30 minutes. When the employee returned back to the drum, he noticed a very small pinhole leak coming from the side, rib area of the drum. The leak was minor and the drum was promptly overpacked and the spill was cleaned up.
column169: Veolia will contact the shipper to recommend the use of a packaging type that is better suited to handle the material such as poly drums. It appears that the material currently being stored in the drums at the shipper's location is corroding through the metal containers over time.
